  "prompt": "What is in the center of a black hole?",
  "response": "The center of a black hole is generally thought to be a singularity, where the gravitational pull is so intense that all matter is crushed to infinitely small points and the concepts of space and time cease to exist as we understand them. In this region, conventional physics breaks down, and our current understanding relies on the framework of general relativity and quantum mechanics, which have not yet been fully reconciled. The singularity represents the limits of our knowledge, and theories such as quantum gravity are being developed to better understand and describe this extreme state.",
